(40, 21, 42, 44, 4, 11, 11, 'the stone which the builders rejected', 'Connection of Rejected Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the ''stone which the builders rejected,'' highlighting its significance as the ''head of the corner.'' This connection illustrates a consistent theme of rejection leading to exaltation.', 'theme', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 42, 60, 2, 4, 8, 'the stone which the builders rejected', 'Connection of Rejected Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of the ''stone which the builders rejected.'' This connection highlights the significance of Jesus as the cornerstone, illustrating his dual role as both precious to believers and a stumbling block to the disobedient.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 42, 49, 2, 20, 20, 'the head of the corner', 'Connection of Cornerstone Imagery', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus as the cornerstone. Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus in the foundation of faith, with Matthew referencing the rejected stone and Ephesians affirming Him as the chief cornerstone.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 42, 45, 9, 33, 33, 'the stone which the builders rejected', 'Rejection of the Cornerstone', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of Jesus as a rejected stone. Matthew highlights the builders rejecting the stone, while Romans presents Him as a stumblingstone for believers.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 42, 41, 12, 10, 11, 'the stone which the builders rejected', 'Connection of Rejected Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase, ''the stone which the builders rejected,'' highlighting a shared theme of rejection and divine purpose. This connection illustrates the significance of the rejected stone becoming the cornerstone, underscoring a common scriptural reference.', 'quotation', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 43, 40, 21, 41, 41, 'fruits', 'Connection of Vineyard and Fruits', 'Both passages emphasize the transfer of the vineyard and the expectation of fruits. Matthew 21:41 speaks of a vineyard being let out to other husbandmen who will render fruits, while Matthew 21:43 states that the kingdom will be given to a nation bringing forth fruits.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 43, 40, 8, 11, 12, 'the kingdom of God shall be taken from you', 'Exclusion from the Kingdom', 'Both passages emphasize the exclusion of certain individuals from the kingdom of heaven. Matthew 21:43 indicates that the kingdom will be taken from one group, while Matthew 8:12 describes the children of the kingdom being cast out.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 43, 60, 2, 9, 9, 'a nation bringing forth the fruits thereof', 'Connection of Nations and Identity', 'This connection highlights the transition of God''s chosen people from Israel to a new community described as a ''holy nation.'' Both passages emphasize the importance of producing ''fruits'' and living in a manner that reflects God''s light.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 43, 43, 3, 3, 3, 'kingdom of God', 'Connection of the Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the kingdom of God. Matthew 21:43 indicates that the kingdom will be given to those who produce its fruits, while John 3:3 states that one must be born again to see the kingdom.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 43, 23, 26, 2, 2, 'nation bringing forth the fruits thereof', 'Connection of Righteous Nations', 'This connection highlights the theme of nations that are deemed righteous. Both passages emphasize the idea of a nation that produces fruits or keeps the truth, indicating a divine expectation of righteousness.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 43, 42, 17, 20, 21, 'kingdom of God', 'Connection of the Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of the kingdom of God. Matthew highlights its transfer to a nation producing fruits, while Luke indicates it is not externally observable but is within individuals.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 43, 2, 19, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Kingdom and Nation', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''kingdom'' and a ''nation'' chosen by God. Matthew 21:43 speaks of the kingdom being given to a nation that produces fruit, while Exodus 19:6 describes Israel as a ''kingdom of priests'' and ''holy nation.'' This connection highlights the transition of God''s chosen people.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 44, 23, 8, 14, 15, 'shall be broken', 'Stumbling and Breaking Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being broken when encountering the stone. Matthew speaks of falling on the stone and being broken, while Isaiah describes many stumbling and falling, leading to being broken.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 44, 60, 2, 8, 8, 'this stone', 'Connection of Stumbling and Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''stone'' that causes division. In Matthew, falling on the stone leads to being broken, while in 1 Peter, it becomes a ''stone of stumbling'' for the disobedient.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 44, 27, 2, 34, 35, 'this stone shall be broken', 'Connection of the Stone Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the destructive power of the stone. In Matthew, the stone causes brokenness or destruction, while in Daniel, the stone breaks the image to pieces, symbolizing judgment and the establishment of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 44, 27, 2, 44, 45, 'this stone', 'Connection of the Stone Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the destructive power of the stone. In Matthew, falling on the stone leads to being broken, while in Daniel, the stone breaks and consumes other kingdoms. This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment and the establishment of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 44, 45, 9, 33, 33, 'this stone', 'Connection of Stumbling and Offense', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a stone that causes division. Matthew speaks of falling on the stone and being broken, while Romans refers to the stone as a stumbling block for those who do not believe.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 44, 42, 20, 18, 18, NULL, 'Connection of Stone Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of falling on the stone, highlighting the theme of brokenness and destruction. The similar wording reinforces the idea of judgment associated with this stone.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 44, 40, 27, 25, 25, 'fall on this stone shall be broken', 'Consequences of Rejecting Christ', 'This connection highlights the consequences of rejecting Jesus as the cornerstone. In Matthew 21:44, falling on the stone leads to being broken, while in Matthew 27:25, the people accept the weight of His blood upon themselves, indicating a rejection that results in dire consequences.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 45, 42, 20, 19, 19, 'they perceived that he spake of them', 'Perception of Parabolic Meaning', 'Both passages emphasize the perception of the chief priests regarding Jesus'' parables. They recognize that he spoke against them, leading to their desire to confront him.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 45, 42, 11, 45, 45, 'spake of them', 'Reproach of Religious Leaders', 'This connection highlights the perception of reproach directed at religious leaders. In both passages, the leaders recognize that Jesus'' words are aimed at them, indicating a shared theme of accountability among those in authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 45, 40, 12, 12, 12, NULL, 'Sabbath and Doing Good', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of doing good, particularly in the context of the Sabbath. In Matthew 21:45, the chief priests and Pharisees recognize that Jesus'' teachings challenge their understanding of righteousness, which is echoed in Matthew 12:12''s assertion of lawful actions on the Sabbath.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 46, 40, 21, 11, 11, 'took him for a prophet', 'Recognition of Jesus as Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as a prophet by the multitude. In Matthew 21:11, the crowd identifies Him explicitly as ''Jesus the prophet,'' while in Matthew 21:46, the authorities fear the multitude because they regard Him as a prophet.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 46, 40, 21, 26, 26, NULL, 'Fear of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of the people regarding prophets. In Matthew 21:46, the multitude views Jesus as a prophet, while in Matthew 21:26, the fear of the people influences the decision about John.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 46, 10, 12, 7, 13, 'took him for a prophet', 'Fear of Prophetic Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in the face of prophetic truth. In both passages, individuals confront the consequences of their actions, with the multitude fearing Jesus as a prophet and David facing Nathan''s prophetic rebuke.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 46, 20, 9, 7, 9, 'they feared the multitude', 'Fear of the Multitude', 'This connection highlights the theme of response to reproof. In Matthew, the multitude''s perception of Jesus as a prophet reflects the idea that wise individuals recognize and respect truth, as seen in Proverbs, where a wise man appreciates rebuke.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 21, 46, 23, 29, 1, 1, 'they feared the multitude', 'Fear of the Prophet', 'This connection highlights the fear of the multitude in Matthew, paralleling the warning in Isaiah about the consequences for the city. Both passages emphasize a sense of impending judgment and the response of the people to prophetic figures.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
